SIMPLE: wilding
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wilding
<hw>Wild"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A wild or
uncultivated plant; especially, a wild apple tree or crab apple; also,
the fruit of such a plant.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ten ruddy <qex>wildings</qex> in the wood I found.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fruit of the tree . . . is small, of little juice, and bad
quality. I presume it to be a <qex>wilding</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wilding</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wilding
<hw>Wild"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Not tame, domesticated, or
cultivated; wild.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wilding</xex>
flowers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ground squirrel gayly chirps by his den,⟦br⟧
And the <qex>wilding</qex> bee hums merrily by.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wildish</ent>⟦br⟧
